<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-827-314  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 827 314.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Sept 3 1990 v35 n18 p93(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Signal sources handle tough timing jobs: crystal oscillators.andO;(includes related articles on getting the right answers andputting the source where its needed)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ormond, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Systems running at hundreds of megahertz require precise, stableclock frequencies, which are possible only through use of crystaloscillators as the clock source.andP;  Among the crystal oscillatoroptions available are uncompensated oscillators,temperature-compensated oscillators (TCOs), digitally compensatedoscillators (DCOs), voltage-controlled oscillators (VCOs) andovenized oscillators.andP;  The application's stability requirementswill determine the type of oscillator used, although designers mayhave to make trade-offs in terms of power consumption andoscillator size.andP;  Simple crystal oscillators generally are used asclocks in digital systems in which stability requirements are nottoo severe; their frequency stability ranges from plus-or-minus100 to plus-or-minus 1,000 ppm.andP;  Oscillators are described fromKDS America, NEL Frequency Controls, Pletronics and Murata Erie.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     OscillatorsSystem DesignClocksTiming CircuitryCircuit DesignFrequencySignal processing.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographtable.andO;Caption:   Representative crystal oscillators. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>